From these opposite premises, a fair and moderate conclusion may be deduced. I am satisfied that Sherefeddin Ali has faithfully ⁵ described the first ostentatious interview, in which the conqueror, whose spirits were harmonised by success, affected the charaeter of generosity. But his mind was insensibly alienated by the unseason- able arrogance of Bajazet3 the complaints of his enemies‚ the Ana- tolian princes, were just and vehement3 and Timour betrayed a design of leading his royal captive in triumph to Samarcand. An attempt to facilitate his escape, by digging a mine under the tent, provoked the Mogul emperor to impose a harsher restraint3 and in his perpetual marehes, an iron cage on a waggon might be invented, not as a wanton insuit, but as a rigorous precaution- Timour had read in some fabulous history a similar treatment of one of his predeceffol‘s‚ a king of Perfia3 and Bajazet was condemned to represent the person, and expiate the guilt, of the Roman Caesar ⁵⁸. But the strength of his mind and body fainted under the trial, and his premature death might, without injustice, be ascribed to the severity of Timour. He warred not with the dead3 a tear and ase- pulchre were all that he could bestow on a captive who was delivered from his power3 and if Mousa‚ the son of Bajazet‚ was permitted

to reign over the ruins of Boursa, the greatest part of the province of Anatolia had been restored by the conqueror to their lawful so- vereigns.
